12 subsection (c)(2) supersedes the authority of an attorney in fact
13 described in subsection (c)(1) to apply for public benefits on behalf of
14 the individual if the individual has specifically granted the authority of
15 the health care representative to supersede the authority of the attorney
16 in fact in the executed power of attorney.
17 (e) Notwithstanding any other law, a document granting health care
18 powers to an attorney in fact for health care may not be executed under
19 this chapter after December 31, 2022. However, if a power of attorney
20 that is executed after December 31, 2022, is written to grant both:
21 (1) health care powers; and
22 (2) nonhealth care powers under this chapter;
23 to an attorney in fact, the health care powers are void, but all other
24 powers granted by the power of attorney will remain effective and
25 enforceable under this article.
26 SECTION 10. IC 32-17-8-3.5, AS ADDED BY P.L.61-2024,
27 SECTION 3, IS AMENDED TO READ AS FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE
28 JULY 1, 2026]: Sec. 3.5. When the an initial power of appointment in
29 a legacy trust is exercised to create a second subsequent power of
30 appointment or nonvested property interest, the subsequent power
31 of appointment or a nonvested property interest or the second power
32 of appointment created through the exercise of the initial power of
33 appointment is considered to have been created at the time of the
34 irrevocable exercise creation of the initial power of appointment,
35 unless:
36 (1) the instrument exercising creating the initial power of
37 appointment; or
38 (2) the instrument exercising the initial power of
39 appointment;
40 explicitly provides that the second subsequent power of appointment
41 was is considered to have been created at the time of the creation
42 irrevocable exercise of the initial power of appointment.
